D. Author

Introduction

Markdown is a markup language that provides very simple styling rules all in plain text. It has an emphasis on allowing the author to concentrate on content rather than formatting.

Its simplicity makes it ideal as a base format from which to convert to other formats such as:

  • html
  • pdf (via LaTeX)
  • word
  • epub
  • etc

pandoc is an open sources universal document converter. Rstudio comes shipped with pandoc.

An Rmarkdown file is a markdown document in which R code is embedded.

An R “chunk” is defined as:

rnorm(100)

When the Rmarkdown document is knitted, the knit() routine evaluates all the R chunks and inserts the output (in markdown format) into the document before it is processed by pandoc to yield the final format.

Images can be embedded, for example:

Equations are included between single $ (for inline equations) and double $$ for blocked equations like:

\(Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 F_i\)

where \(y_i\) is the response.

Mathematical formulae are processed using mathjax (for html and word) or LaTeX for pdf.
